"{\"uid\": \"rollingstone.com-product-recommendations-lifestyle-watch-paris-2024-olympics-closing-ceremony-online-free-livestream-1235077548\", \"text\": \"ByOscar Hartzog  If you purchase an independently reviewed product or service through a link on our website, Rolling Stone may receive an affiliate commission.  After two weeks of non-stop action, the2024 Paris Olympicsare coming to a close. On Sunday, the festivities wrap up with a closing ceremony, delivering some final excitement from France.    Just like the opening ceremony, the closing ceremony has become a major draw forOlympicsviewers thanks to A-listperformancesand a grand parade of athletes. The ceremony will include a symbolic handover from this year's host, Paris, to the 2028 Summer Olympics host, Los Angeles. Billie Eilish, Snoop Dogg, and the Red Hot Chili Peppers are expected to perform for the event, andTom Cruisewill be pulling off aMission Impossible-style stunt.  Below, we have put together a quick guide on how to watch the Olympics closing ceremony, including a way tolivestreamthe closing ceremony for free.  The Paris Olympics closing ceremony is airing live on NBC and streaming onPeacock. However, another option for cord-cutters is to get afree trial to a live TV streaming servicethat carries NBC, such asDirecTV Stream,fubo, orHulu + Live TV.  All of these cable streaming services offerfree trials- running from three to seven days - that you can use to stream the closing ceremony for free. Just remember to cancel the trial before it ends to avoid being charged. If you want to watch the closing ceremony on Peacock, sign up for asubscription herefor $7.99 a month (Peacock does not offer a free trial, unfortunately).  No matter which option you choose, you will be able to watch the closing ceremony online from home. Plus, all of these options will offer livestreams of Olympic events scheduled to take place on Sunday before the ceremony, including women's basketball, cycling, volleyball, and wrestling.  The 2024 Olympics closing ceremony is happening on Sunday, Aug. 11. The ceremony starts at 2 p.m. ET/11 a.m. PT for US viewers.  This year's Olympics closing ceremony will feature live broadcasts from both Paris and Los Angeles, as well as prerecorded segments. NBC's coverage will be hosted by Jimmy Fallon and Mike Tirico with supporting commentary from Olympians Johnny Weir and Tara Lipinski.  Just like the opening ceremony, there will also be some performances from major acts including Billie Eilish, Snoop Dogg, and the Red Hot Chili Peppers, according toreports. The performances will be a mix of live broadcasts and pre-recorded content, all from Los Angeles.  One of the most highly-anticipated segments of the closing ceremony is a flag-transfer by Tom Cruise. TheMission Impossiblestar willreportedlyrepeal down the Stade de France on live TV, before the broadcast cuts to a prerecorded clip of the movie star skydiving down the Hollywood sign in Los Angeles.  We want to hear it. Send us a tip using our anonymous form.  Rolling Stone is a part of Penske Media Corporation. \\u00a9 2026 Rolling Stone, LLC. All rights reserved.\"}"